3. Function Overloading

Aim:
To demonstrate function overloading in a class.
To perform operations using the same function name.

Algorithm:

1. Start the program.
2. Define a class containing overloaded functions.
3. Use different parameter lists for the same function name.
4. Create an object in main().
5. Call the overloaded functions with different arguments.
6. Display all the results.
7. Stop the program.
Program:


#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Math {
public:
    int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    double add(double a, double b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    int add(int a, int b, int c) {
        return a + b + c;
    }
};

int main() {
    Math obj;
    cout << "Sum of two integers: " << obj.add(5, 10) << endl;
    cout << "Sum of two doubles: " << obj.add(4.5, 3.2) << endl;
    cout << "Sum of three integers: " << obj.add(2, 3, 4) << endl;
    return 0;
}


Output:


Sum of two integers: 15
Sum of two doubles: 7.7
Sum of three integers: 9


Result:
Function overloading was successfully applied to class members.
Different versions of the same function executed correctly.
